On the other hand, St. Joseph reached this state of mercy after many decades of prayer, fasting, and purifying his heart, so if any of us share the same outward "stance", it is most likely out of false humility, and in our hearts we would love our enemies humiliated and tortured.

La Rochefoucauld is basically Christian psychoanalysis. You do not fear death? It is because you fear death so much, that your only choice as not to go insane with fear is to pretend that you do not do so. You fear death because you are sinful. All your virtues are secretly sins.

Nietzsche probably liked the moral maxims so much, because you can legitimately go insane if you follow through them like a labyrinth. They connect to each other and the fundamental conclusion is that every part of your personality is either a vice or a mechanism to cover a vice.

Humility is our attempt to supplant our superiors out of our pride. We are sadistic in our mercy and forgiveness over enemies, because it is an ultimate show of superiority. Any sensual sin (lust, etc.) submitted is transformed into pride. At the end you are left with nothing.
